<div class="artlayout">
<div class="artbody">
<div style="display:flex;gap:7px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px"><span class="tg tgb">Home Loans</span><span class="tg tgb">CIBIL Score</span><span style="font-size:11.5px;color:var(--grn)">✓ Updated March 20, 2026</span><span style="font-size:11.5px;color:var(--ash)">8 min read</span></div>
<h1 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:26px;font-style:italic;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.1;margin-bottom:9px;font-weight:400">How your CIBIL score <em style="color:var(--saf)">directly determines</em> your home loan interest rate</h1>
<div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--ash);display:flex;gap:11px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:14px"><span>By <strong>InvestingPro Research Team</strong></span><span>Fact-checked: March 2026</span></div>
<div class="ktbox"><div class="ktlbl">Key Takeaways</div><div class="kti">A CIBIL score difference of 50 points can change your home loan rate by 0.5% — ₹4.8 lakh more interest on ₹60L over 20 years.</div><div class="kti">Scores of 800+ qualify for the bank's best advertised rates. Below 700 typically pays 1–2% higher.</div><div class="kti">Use our CIBIL Simulator to see your exact score impact before applying — 2 minutes, zero cost.</div><div class="kti">You can improve your CIBIL score by 40–60 points in 3–6 months with the right actions.</div></div>

<p>Banks advertise their lowest home loan rate — say 8.35% — but that rate is only for borrowers with a CIBIL score above 800. If your score is 720, you'll be offered 8.85% or higher. The difference sounds small. It isn't.</p>
<div class="pullq"><div class="pqt">"The bank won't tell you how much more they charge based on your credit score. We will."</div><div class="pqs">InvestingPro Research · March 2026</div></div>

<h2>The rate table banks don't publish — <em>by CIBIL band</em></h2>
<table class="dt"><tr><th>CIBIL Band</th><th>SBI Rate</th><th>EMI / ₹60L / 20yr</th><th>vs 800+</th></tr><tr><td><strong>800+</strong></td><td class="dg">8.35%</td><td>₹51,782</td><td><span class="dtag dtag-g">Best rate</span></td></tr><tr><td>750–799</td><td>8.60%</td><td>₹52,806</td><td class="dw">+₹2.46L total</td></tr><tr><td>700–749</td><td>8.85%</td><td>₹53,835</td><td class="dr">+₹4.93L total</td></tr><tr><td>Below 700</td><td class="dr">9.35%+</td><td>₹55,913</td><td class="dr">+₹9.9L total</td></tr></table>

<h2>The 5 CIBIL factors — <em>what each one means</em></h2>
<h3>1. Payment history (35%) — the most important</h3>
<p>Every EMI payment and credit card bill is reported to CIBIL. Miss one payment and your score drops 40–60 points instantly. Pay on time for 12 consecutive months and it recovers by 25–40 points.</p>
<h3>2. Credit utilisation (30%) — the one you can fix fastest</h3>
<p>This is the percentage of your total credit card limit that you're using. If you have cards with a ₹2 lakh limit and you've spent ₹1.5 lakh, your utilisation is 75% — which significantly damages your score. Keep it below 30% for the best impact. Below 10% is optimal.</p>
<h3>3. Credit age (15%)</h3>
<p>The longer your credit history, the better. This is why closing your oldest credit card can hurt your score — it shortens your average credit age. Keep old cards alive, even if you barely use them.</p>

<h2>90-day improvement plan — <em>actionable steps</em></h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Month 1:</strong> Pay down the highest-utilisation card first. Going from 80% to 40% on one card adds 15–20 points.</li>
<li><strong>Month 2:</strong> Set up auto-pay for all EMIs. Not a single missed payment for the next 90 days.</li>
<li><strong>Month 3:</strong> Check your CIBIL report for errors. 18% of Indian credit reports contain at least one error. Dispute them via CIBIL's online portal — errors corrected typically add 20–40 points.</li>
</ul>

<h2>FAQs</h2>
<div class="faqi"><div class="faqq" onclick="togFAQ(this)">How long does it take to improve a CIBIL score?</div><div class="faqa">Most people see 30–50 points improvement within 3–6 months of consistent on-time payments and reduced utilisation. Serious damage (missed EMI, settled account) takes 12–24 months to recover from, as the mark stays on your report for 7 years but diminishes over time.</div></div>
<div class="faqi"><div class="faqq" onclick="togFAQ(this)">Does checking my own CIBIL score reduce it?</div><div class="faqa">No. Checking your own score is a "soft enquiry" and has zero impact. Only "hard enquiries" — when a bank pulls your score for a loan or card application — affect your score. Each hard enquiry reduces your score by approximately 5–10 points.</div></div>
<div class="faqi"><div class="faqq" onclick="togFAQ(this)">What is a good CIBIL score for a home loan?</div><div class="faqa">750 or above qualifies for best advertised rates at most PSU banks. 800+ unlocks absolute best rates. Most banks approve loans for 700+ at higher rates. Below 650, most banks reject or charge very high rates.</div></div>
<div class="faqi"><div class="faqq" onclick="togFAQ(this)">How often is CIBIL score updated?</div><div class="faqa">CIBIL receives data from member banks monthly. Your score is recalculated when new data arrives. Major changes (paying off a card, a new EMI) typically reflect within 30–45 days.</div></div>
</div>
